  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.8090" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <dateline>Panjab Notes &amp;amp; Queries<lb/> EDITORS‘ OFFICE <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Dated 20-11 1885</hi>
          <lb/> [Hs. hinzugefügt: Naval &amp;amp; Military Club 94 Picadilly London E. C.] </dateline>
        <opener>Dear Sir,</opener>
        <p>very many thanks for your letter of 26 Sept. forwarded to me here. I am home on two years‘ prolong. for my health. I am sorry yours has been bad.</p>
        <p>Your queries in the April n° 1884<note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">Dieser Beitrag Schuchardts konnte trotz Durchsicht der Zeitschrift nicht identifiziert werden.</note> were not directly answered but they gave rise to many notes on points you are interested in on Indo-English and the various ways English &amp;amp; the Portuguese &amp;amp; other languages are being corrupted in India.</p>
        <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>

        <p>I don’t suppose you are likely to get anything out of „Grip“: it is only an ordinary novel written by a very flighty lady who has never enjoyed much reputation either morally or as a writer.<note
            n="2" place="foot" type="editorial">Nicht identifiziert.</note>
        </p>
        <p>I am making great efforts to convert my „<ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.5465">Panjab Notes</ref>“ into an „Indian Notes and Queries“, which will I hope be useful to every body interested in the East. It is a great undertaking.</p>
        <closer>
          <salute>Yours respectfully</salute>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2844">RC Temple</persName>
          </signed>
        </closer>
      </div>
    </body>
